static ssize_t read_mem(struct file *file, char __user *buf,<br />&gt;                 sz = size_inside_page(p, count);<br />&gt;                 cond_resched();<br />&gt;                 err = -EINTR;<br />&gt; -               if (fatal_signal_pending(current))<br />&gt; +               if (signal_pending(current))<br />&gt;                         goto failed;<br />&gt;<br />&gt;                 err = -EPERM;<br /><br />So from a "likelihood of breaking" standpoint, I'd really like to make<br />sure that the "signal_pending()" checks come at the *end* of the loop.<br /><br />That way, if somebody is doing a 4-byte read from MMIO, he'll never see -EINTR.<br /><br />I'm specifically thinking of tools like user-space 'lspci' etc, which<br />I wouldn't be surprised could happen.<br /><br />Also, just in case things break, I do agree with Ingo that this should<br />be split up into several patches.<br /><br />             Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
